The paper discusses a new frequency domain model of human joint dynamics and its implications for control of performance augmentation exoskeletons. This topic falls under the field of robotics and control systems, which suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.RO (Robotics) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of a fractional order controller, which is a common technique in the field of control systems, further supporting the likelihood of the paper belonging to the cs.RO sub-category. 

The paper also discusses the interaction between physical human and robot, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. 

The paper involves experimentation with an elbow-joint exoskeleton testbed, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.ME (Mechanical Engineering) sub-category. 

The paper discusses the implications of the complex stiffness model for human-computer interaction, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper discusses the human joint dynamics and its implications for performance augmentation exoskeletons, which suggests that it may also belong to the cs.BIO (Computational Biology) sub-category.
